It is always with gladness, dear Mr Bentham, that I receive letters from you. If I have not often adressed you within the last few years, you must seek the cause in my reluctance of encroaching on your valuable time, which with your unimpaired energy you devote still to such important and difficult subjects in phytographic science. I renew my wish, that you may be spared for scientific purposes to an age like that of Humboldt, and longer still.
Humboldt was almost 90 when he died. I look forward with deep interest to the part of your & Hooker's celebrated "genera plantarum", containing the Monocotyledoneae and the Supplements;
Published in April 1883 in Part 2 of vol. 3 of Bentham & Hooker (1862-83). and still hope, that you and he will be induced to see the work really completed by the aid of great workers on "Evasculares", such as Berkeley, Agardh and other specialists before they pass away.
